## The Latest Quarter At A Glance

Data on India's Gross Domestic Product for Quarter 2 of the 2024-25 fiscal year has just been published. Here are some highlights:

-   Inflation-adjusted Gross Domestic Product was INR 4,410,322.90 crores at constant 2011-12 prices. (A crore is ten million or 10<sup>7</sup>.)\
-   This represents a growth of [5.36 percent]{style="color: red;"} compared to the same quarter in the previous fiscal year. (The available quarterly data spans Quarter 1 of the 2011-12 fiscal year through Quarter 2 of the 2024-25 fiscal year. That's 13 years. Over the past 13 years, GDP has grown [6.1 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Consumption spending grew [5.96 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, consumption spending has grown [6.26 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Investment spending grew [5.92 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, investment spending has grown [5.49 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Government purchases grew [4.43 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, government purchases has grown [3.47 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)\
-   Exports grew [2.84 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, exports has grown [5.56 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Imports grew [-2.89 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, imports has grown [4.35 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Net Exports grew [40.46 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 13 years, net exports has grown [2.17 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Summary of the latest quarter: **Weaker than usual. GDP growth was below the long-run average, dragged down by slower growth in consumption spending. Investment spending and government purchases both grew faster than they usually do. Exports grew significantly slower than usual. Imports shrank.**

